03890nam a22006615i 9780801471377DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014713777 a10.7591/97808014713772doi  a(DE-B1597)515845  a(OCoLC)1083592294  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0150002bisacsh04a152.42221 aBrennan, Teresa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Transmission of Affect /cTeresa Brennan. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tCHAPTER ONE. Introduction -- tCHAPTER TWO. The Transmission of Affect in the Clinic -- tCHAPTER THREE. Transmission in Groups -- tCHAPTER FOUR. The New Paradigm -- tCHAPTER FIVE. The Sealing of the Heart -- tCHAPTER SIX. The Education of the Senses -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Interpreting the Flesh -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe idea that one can soak up someone else's depression or anxiety or sense the tension in a room is familiar. Indeed, phrases that capture this notion abound in the popular vernacular: "negative energy," "dumping," "you could cut the tension with a knife." The Transmission of Affect deals with the belief that the emotions and energies of one person or group can be absorbed by or can enter directly into another.The ability to borrow or share states of mind, once historically and culturally assumed, is now pathologized, as Teresa Brennan shows in relation to affective transfer in psychiatric clinics and the prevalence of psychogenic illness in contemporary life. To neglect the mechanism by which affect is transmitted, the author claims, has serious consequences for science and medical research.Brennan's theory of affect is based on constant communication between individuals and their physical and social environments. Her important book details the relationships among affect, energy, and "new maladies of the soul," including attention deficit disorder, chronic fatigue syndrome, codependency, and fibromyalgia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAffect (Psychology)xSocial aspects. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Mind & Body.2bisacsh1 aTeachout, Woden, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147137740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801471377423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801471377/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK